Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Dangote Sugar, Standard Chartered Bank Kenya

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-03-08T16:01:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-dangote-sugar-national-bank-of-kenya.html
  Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell to the
lowest since July 7, dropping 1.2 percent to 74.62 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index retreated 0.3
percent to 25,174.24 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to an e-mailed statement from the bourse. That’s a 10th day of
declines, matching the longest losing streak since August 2009.
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index fell for a sixth day, losing 0.1
percent to 2,012.39 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .    Namibia ’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  slipped for a third
day, losing 1.7 percent to 879.27 by 5 p.m. in Windhoek, while
the Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index added 0.4 percent to
close at 1,057.88 by 3 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    Dangote Sugar Refinery Plc (DANGSUGA)  , a Nigerian
producer of the sweetener, dropped to the lowest since March
2009, retreating 41 kobo, or 2.9 percent, to 13.62 naira.
Stanbic IBTC Plc reduced its recommendation on the stock to
“sell” from “buy” and cut its price estimate to 15.5 naira
from 23 naira.    National Bank of Kenya Ltd. (NBKL)  , a state-run lender,
fell the most in seven months, losing 2 shillings, or 4.4
percent, to 43.75 shillings. “Fund managers have halted their
decisions and foreign investors are not in the market,” George Bodo, an analyst with Nairobi-based Genghis Capital Ltd., said
in a phone interview today. “The market is being driven by
retail pullout.”  He expects the bank to report full-year earnings next week.
National Bank will release its earnings “soon,” Corporate
Affairs Manager Rebecca Gikuru said today in response to an e-
mailed question.    Standard Chartered Bank Kenya Ltd. (SCBL)  , the country’s
third-biggest lender by market value, fell to its lowest level
in two months, slumping 9 shillings, or 3.4 percent, to 260
shillings, on concern that its profitability is lagging that of
rivals.  “With close to 75 percent of its loan book under wholesale
banking,” the Standard Chartered Plc unit “continued to record
a below-industry net interest margin of 7.7 percent,” African
Alliance Securities Kenya Ltd. wrote in an e-mailed note to
clients. There will be “no immediate improvement in net
interest margin as spreads in wholesale banking remain low due
to competition,” the brokerage wrote.  To contact the reporter on this story:
